		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>146 Chestnut St</placeName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>March 3 1849</date></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">My dear sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">A gentleman by the name of<lb/> <persName>Berk</persName> said to be a Polish Jew converted to Christianity<lb/> has a plate or picture of <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName> &#38; a history of the<lb/> city and professes to be familiar with its history &#38;c.<lb/>  I do not expect that you will give me any opinion<lb/> respecting the genuineness of his supposed conversion&#44; but<lb/> I would be obliged if you will tell me whether you know<lb/> any thing to his prejudice apart from this.  I have<lb/> been asked to secure his admission to lecture to an assembly<lb/> I should be sorry to introduce him&#44; if his <hi rend="underline">moral char</hi>&#45;<lb/><hi rend="underline">acter</hi> &#38; standing are not irreproachable your reply<lb/> will be confidential.Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Fred A Packard</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p><addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>371 Walnut St</placeName></p>
		</body>
